  <div class="protocol-card">
    <div class="header">
      <h1>Ch. 5 üö® Critical Care</h1>
      <p>Shock Recognition & Resuscitation ‚Ä¢ Vasopressors & Inotropes ‚Ä¢ Invasive Hemodynamics ‚Ä¢ Mechanical Ventilation ‚Ä¢ ARDS</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Opening Map -->
    <div class="intro">
      <div class="intro-h"><h2 style="margin:0">üìã Opening Map ‚Äî What the Chapter Covers</h2></div>
      <div class="grid-2" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
        <div class="callout scope">
          <h3 style="margin:0 0 10px 0; color: var(--blueDeep); font-size:16px;">üéØ Scope</h3>
          <p style="margin:0; font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">Rapid identification and initial management of <strong>hypovolemic, distributive (septic/anaphylactic/neurogenic), cardiogenic, and obstructive shock</strong>; choosing pressors/inotropes; reading <strong>PCWP/CI/SVR</strong>; setting and titrating the ventilator; diagnosing and treating <strong>ARDS</strong>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="callout times">
          <h3 style="margin:0 0 10px 0; color:#f57c00; font-size:16px;">‚è∞ Time-Critical Nuggets</h3>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>ABCs first</strong>; fluids early in most shock states</li>
            <li><strong>Norepinephrine</strong> is the workhorse vasopressor for septic shock</li>
            <li>Avoid fluids in acute <strong>cardiogenic shock</strong> or TBI with severe ICP</li>
            <li><strong>Golden hour</strong> for sepsis: cultures + antibiotics within 1 hour</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout themes">
        <h3 style="margin:0 0 12px 0; color:#7b1fa2; font-size:16px;">üî• High‚ÄëYield Themes</h3>
        <div class="grid-2" style="gap:15px;">
          <ul style="margin:0;">
            <li><strong>Clinical signs:</strong> Warm skin ‚Üí distributive; cold/clammy ‚Üí hypo-, cardio-, or obstructive shock</li>
            <li><strong>Bradycardic shock:</strong> think neurogenic</li>
            <li>NS in very large volumes ‚Üí hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis; prefer <strong>LR for big boluses</strong></li>
          </ul>
          <ul style="margin:0;">
            <li><strong>PCWP</strong> (preload, left heart, bad if >18) up in cardiogenic/obstructive, down in hypovolemic</li>
            <li><strong>PaO‚ÇÇ/FiO‚ÇÇ < 200</strong> + bilateral infiltrates + PCWP ‚â§ 18 ‚Üí ARDS</li>
            <li><strong>Vent settings:</strong> Vt 6-8 mL/kg IBW; FiO‚ÇÇ ‚â§ 60%; PEEP 5</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Base Cases -->
    <div class="content">
      <!-- Case 1: Septic Shock -->
      <div class="case">
        <div class="case-header">üî• Base Case 1<br>"Hot, hypotensive, confused"</div>
        <div class="patient-info">
          <strong>Patient:</strong> 68-year-old man, fever and cough for 3 days, confused, BP 78/40, HR 126, RR 28, T <span class="temperature">39.4¬∞C</span>, warm extremities, bounding pulses, UOP scant<br/>
          <strong>Exam:</strong> Warm, flushed skin; no JVD; coarse breath sounds in RLL
        </div>
        <div class="section differential">
          <div class="section-title">üîç Top Differential</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Septic shock</strong> (PNA) most likely from pneumonia; anaphylaxis (no exposure/urticaria), adrenal crisis, neurogenic shock (no bradycardia/SCI)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section next-step">
          <div class="section-title">‚ö° Next Best Step</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Large-bore IV/IO, <strong>balanced crystalloid bolus</strong> (LR, 30 mL/kg), send cultures, start <strong>broad-spectrum antibiotics within the golden hour</strong> (first 1 hr)</li>
            <li>Search for source, give <strong>norepinephrine if MAP < 65</strong> after fluids</li>
            <li>Glucose control (target <180). UOP monitoring</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section findings">
          <div class="section-title">üìä Add Data: Lactate 5.2; BP stays 82/44 after 30 mL/kg LR bolus</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Start <strong>norepinephrine</strong> (first-line vasopressor), consider vasopressin add-on if refractory</li>
            <li>Evaluate for source control (drain empyema, remove infected line)</li>
            <li><span class="highlight">Avoid dopamine</span> as the first pressor - less effective and more arrhythmogenic</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section what-if">
          <div class="section-title">üîÄ Alternate Forks</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Immunosuppressed/neutropenic:</strong> keep broadest coverage; early source control</li>
            <li><strong>Atrial fibrillation w/ RVR:</strong> cautiously control rate (esmolol), treat sepsis first</li>
            <li><strong>Pulmonary edema after large fluids:</strong> transition earlier to pressors; consider diuretics once perfusion restored</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section takeaway">
          <div class="section-title">üéØ Takeaways & Traps</div>
          <ul>
            <li><span class="highlight">SEPSIS BUNDLE:</span> 30 mL/kg LR, norepinephrine to MAP ‚â•65, antibiotics within 1 hour, source control</li>
            <li>Don't delay antibiotics for imaging</li>
            <li>Warm skin in shock = distributive</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Case 2: Hypovolemic Shock -->
      <div class="case">
        <div class="case-header">ü©∏ Base Case 2<br>"Pale, cool, post-trauma"</div>
        <div class="patient-info">
          <strong>Patient:</strong> 24-year-old after MVC; HR 140, BP 84/50, cool clammy skin, anxious, UOP minimal<br/>
          <strong>Exam:</strong> Diffuse abdominal tenderness; no breath sounds in the L apex
        </div>
        <div class="section differential">
          <div class="section-title">üîç Top Differential</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Hypovolemic hemorrhagic shock</strong> (likely from abdominal bleeding) ¬± tension pneumothorax</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section next-step">
          <div class="section-title">‚ö° Next Best Step</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Two large-bore IVs, <strong>LR bolus</strong> while activating hemorrhage control‚Äîcall surgery, activate <strong>MTP</strong> (massive transfusion protocol)</li>
            <li>Consider blood if class III‚ÄìIV shock</li>
            <li><strong>Treat tension pneumothorax if suspected</strong> (needle ‚Üí chest tube) before x-ray</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section findings">
          <div class="section-title">üìä Add Data: FAST positive; BP transiently improves with fluids, then drops</div>
          <ul>
            <li><span class="critical">Urgent operative/IR control of bleeding IMMEDIATELY</span></li>
            <li>Type & cross; <strong>balanced transfusion</strong> if massive hemorrhage</li>
            <li><strong>1:1:1 ratio</strong> (PRBCs:Plasma:Platelets)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section what-if">
          <div class="section-title">üîÄ Alternate Forks</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Œ≤-blocked athlete:</strong> tachycardia blunted‚Äîdon't miss shock; rely on mental status, skin, and UOP</li>
            <li><strong>Burns/third-spacing:</strong> still hypovolemic even without hemorrhage; aggressive crystalloid early (LR)</li>
            <li><strong>Elderly on diuretics:</strong> hypovolemia with orthostasis and prerenal azotemia; careful repletion</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section takeaway">
          <div class="section-title">üí° Pearls</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Cold, clammy = non-distributive shock</li>
            <li>NS in huge volume ‚Üí hyperchloremic acidosis‚Äî<strong>prefer LR</strong></li>
            <li><strong>UOP ‚â•0.5 mL/kg/hr</strong> = key resuscitation endpoint</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Case 3: Neurogenic Shock -->
      <div class="case">
        <div class="case-header">üß† Base Case 3<br>"Bradycardic shock after C-spine injury"</div>
        <div class="patient-info">
          <strong>Patient:</strong> 35yo fall; flaccid paralysis below C6; BP 78/40, HR 52; warm skin, no JVD<br/>
          <strong>Classic Triad:</strong> Hypotension + Bradycardia + Warm Skin
        </div>
        <div class="section findings">
          <div class="section-title">üéØ Diagnosis</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Neurogenic shock</strong> from cervical cord injury</li>
            <li>Loss of sympathetic tone ‚Üí vasodilation + bradycardia</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section next-step">
          <div class="section-title">‚ö° Next Best Step - ABCDE Approach</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Airway:</strong> Protect early‚Äîhigh spinal injury risk (C3-C5 diaphragm compromise)</li>
            <li><strong>Breathing:</strong> Assess respiratory function; early intubation if needed</li>
            <li><strong>Circulation:</strong> IV fluids; if unresponsive, start vasopressors (norepinephrine or phenylephrine)</li>
            <li><strong>Atropine</strong> for profound bradycardia (unopposed vagal tone)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section what-if">
          <div class="section-title">üîÄ Forks</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Hypothermia present:</strong> rewarm; bradycardia may persist</li>
            <li><strong>Concomitant hemorrhage:</strong> mixed picture‚Äîuse exam/bedside echo to differentiate</li>
            <li><strong>Airway not protected:</strong> early intubation (GCS ‚â§8 ‚Üí intubate)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section takeaway">
          <div class="section-title">üí° Management Sequence</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Fluid resuscitation for shock/hypotension</li>
            <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Atropine for symptomatic bradycardia (HR <50)</li>
            <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Vasopressors for persistent hypotension</li>
            <li>Avoid over-resuscitation‚Äîthese patients cannot compensate for volume overload</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Case 4: Cardiogenic Shock -->
      <div class="case">
        <div class="case-header">üíî Base Case 4<br>"Crushing chest pain with pulmonary edema"</div>
        <div class="patient-info">
          <strong>Patient:</strong> 64-year-old with acute MI; BP 86/54, HR 118, cool, clammy, JVD, rales, S3<br/>
          <strong>Hemodynamics:</strong> PCWP 24, CI 1.6, SVR high
        </div>
        <div class="section findings">
          <div class="section-title">üéØ Type of Shock</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Cardiogenic shock</strong> 2/2 MI</li>
            <li>High PCWP + low CO + high SVR = cardiogenic profile</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section next-step">
          <div class="section-title">‚ö° First Steps</div>
          <ul>
            <li>O‚ÇÇ, analgesia (morphine), correct electrolytes (K/Mg)</li>
            <li><strong>Cautious pressors/inotropes:</strong> norepinephrine for MAP, dobutamine to augment CO</li>
            <li><strong>Revascularization if MI</strong> (with PCI or CABG)</li>
            <li><strong>IABP</strong> for refractory cases</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section takeaway">
          <div class="section-title">üí° Key Points</div>
          <ul>
            <li>High PCWP + low CO + high SVR = cardiogenic/obstructive</li>
            <li>Treat cause and support perfusion</li>
            <li>Avoid excessive fluids - will worsen pulmonary edema</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Case 5: Obstructive Shock -->
      <div class="case">
        <div class="case-header">üö´ Base Case 5<br>"Sudden PEA arrest after femur fracture"</div>
        <div class="patient-info">
          <strong>Patient:</strong> 38-year-old POD1 ORIF; sudden dyspnea ‚Üí PEA
        </div>
        <div class="section differential">
          <div class="section-title">üîç Top DDx</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Massive PE</strong> (obstructive shock) vs tension pneumothorax vs cardiac tamponade</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section next-step">
          <div class="section-title">‚ö° Next Best Step</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Immediate ACLS protocol</strong></li>
            <li>If high suspicion of PE and unstable: <strong>thrombolysis</strong> (alteplase) or embolectomy</li>
            <li>For tension pneumothorax: <strong>needle decompression now</strong></li>
            <li>For tamponade: <strong>pericardiocentesis</strong></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section takeaway">
          <div class="section-title">üí° Key Principle</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Obstructive shock = treat the obstruction/remove physical blockage</strong></li>
            <li>(PE, tension PTX, tamponade)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Case 6: Mechanical Ventilation -->
      <div class="case">
        <div class="case-header">ü´Å Base Case 6<br>"You just intubated‚Äîwhat vent settings?"</div>
        <div class="patient-info">
          <strong>Patient:</strong> 72-year-old septic with increased WOB ‚Üí intubated
        </div>
        <div class="section next-step">
          <div class="section-title">‚ö° Initial Ventilator Settings</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Mode:</strong> Assist-Control (AC)</li>
            <li><strong>RR:</strong> 12‚Äì16</li>
            <li><strong>Vt:</strong> 6‚Äì8 mL/kg ideal body weight (correlates with height, not weight)</li>
            <li><strong>FiO‚ÇÇ:</strong> 100% then titrate down</li>
            <li><strong>PEEP:</strong> 5 cm H‚ÇÇO (prevents alveolar collapse)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section management">
          <div class="section-title">üîß Adjusting Settings</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Ventilation (PaCO‚ÇÇ/pH):</strong> change minute ventilation (RR or Vt) ‚Äî <em>this is all about CO‚ÇÇ removal</em></li>
            <li><strong>Oxygenation (PaO‚ÇÇ/SpO‚ÇÇ):</strong> change FiO‚ÇÇ and/or PEEP ‚Äî <em>this is all about getting O‚ÇÇ in</em></li>
            <li>Keep FiO‚ÇÇ ‚â§ 60% to limit oxygen toxicity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section what-if">
          <div class="section-title">üîÄ What If Forks</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Hypercapnia (High PaCO‚ÇÇ):</strong> ‚ÜëRR or ‚ÜëVt (watch plateau pressure)</li>
            <li><strong>Hypoxemia despite FiO‚ÇÇ 60%:</strong> ‚ÜëPEEP cautiously</li>
            <li><strong>Weaning trial:</strong> consider PSV/CPAP; common failures = anxiety, excess sedation, hypophosphatemia, diaphragm weakness, overfeeding</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section takeaway">
          <div class="section-title">üéØ Complications & Pearls</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Complications:</strong> barotrauma (tension PTX), ‚Üìvenous return/hypotension, VAP</li>
            <li><strong>PaCO‚ÇÇ = ventilation; PaO‚ÇÇ = oxygenation</strong></li>
            <li>PEEP improves oxygenation but may drop BP</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Case 7: ARDS -->
      <div class="case">
        <div class="case-header">üí® Base Case 7<br>"Refractory hypoxemia with new bilateral opacities"</div>
        <div class="patient-info">
          <strong>Patient:</strong> 55-year-old with pancreatitis; dyspneic, hypoxemic; CXR: bilateral fluffy infiltrates; PaO‚ÇÇ/FiO‚ÇÇ 150; PCWP 12
        </div>
        <div class="section findings">
          <div class="section-title">üéØ Diagnosis</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>ARDS</strong> - "leaky lungs"</li>
            <li><strong>Criteria:</strong> bilateral infiltrates + PaO‚ÇÇ/FiO‚ÇÇ < 200 + no left heart failure (PCWP ‚â§ 18) + acute onset</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section next-step">
          <div class="section-title">‚ö° Next Best Step</div>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Low tidal volume ventilation</strong> (6 mL/kg), adequate PEEP</li>
            <li>Treat cause (pancreatitis/sepsis)</li>
            <li>Keep FiO‚ÇÇ ‚â§ 60% when possible (to avoid O‚ÇÇ toxicity)</li>
            <li>Intubate if needed; <strong>avoid fluid overload</strong></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section management">
          <div class="section-title">üè• ICU Management</div>
          <ul>
            <li>All ARDS patients need ICU</li>
            <li>Consider <strong>prone positioning</strong> (on their belly) if refractory</li>
            <li>Higher PEEP if refractory hypoxemia</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="section takeaway">
          <div class="section-title">üí° Pathophysiology</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Inflammatory lung injury with ‚Üëpermeability</li>
            <li>V/Q mismatch, ‚Üìcompliance</li>
            <li>Risk of barotrauma with high pressures</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Template B: Hemodynamics/Imaging/Labs -->
    <div class="intro">
      <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--amber) 0%, var(--amberDeep) 100%);">üìä Template B ‚Äî Hemodynamics/Imaging/Labs</div>
      <div class="tiles">
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--green);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--green);">PCWP (PA catheter)</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
            <p><strong>Shows:</strong> LV end-diastolic surrogate (preload)</p>
            <p><strong>Indications:</strong> Differentiate cardiogenic vs ARDS; unclear volume status</p>
            <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> PCWP >18 favors CHF; ‚â§18 favors ARDS. Use with CO/SVR to profile shock</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">Cardiac Output / CI</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
            <p><strong>Shows:</strong> Pump performance</p>
            <p><strong>Use:</strong> Shock of unclear etiology</p>
            <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> Low CI + high SVR ‚Üí cardiogenic; low CI + low SVR ‚Üí distributive</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--indigo);">SVR (Systemic Vascular Resistance)</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
            <p><strong>Shows:</strong> Systemic tone (afterload)</p>
            <p><strong>Use:</strong> Profiling shock</p>
            <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> Very low SVR ‚Üí distributive. Combine with CI/PCWP</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--magenta);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--magenta);">CXR</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
            <p><strong>Shows:</strong> Edema, PTX, lines</p>
            <p><strong>Indications:</strong> Dyspnea, vent complications</p>
            <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> New tension PTX ‚Üí immediate needle decompression</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--amber);">ABG</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
            <p><strong>Shows:</strong> Oxygenation/ventilation status</p>
            <p><strong>Use:</strong> Adjust vent settings</p>
            <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> PaO‚ÇÇ low ‚Üí ‚ÜëFiO‚ÇÇ/PEEP; PaCO‚ÇÇ high ‚Üí ‚Üëminute ventilation</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Template C: Pharmacology (Pressors/Inotropes) -->
    <div class="intro">
      <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--magenta) 0%, var(--magentaDeep) 100%);">üíä Template C ‚Äî Pharmacology (Pressors/Inotropes)</div>
      <div class="tiles" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(350px, 1fr));">
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--green);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--green);">Norepinephrine (Levophed)</div>
          <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
            <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 0.02‚Äì0.3 Œºg/kg/min</p>
            <p><strong>MOA:</strong> Œ±1‚â´Œ≤1 (vasoconstrictor with modest inotropy)</p>
            <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> First-line in septic shock</p>
            <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Ischemia, arrhythmias</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--indigo);">Dobutamine (Dobutrex)</div>
          <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
            <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 2‚Äì20 Œºg/kg/min</p>
            <p><strong>MOA:</strong> Œ≤1>Œ≤2 (inotrope, mild vasodilation)</p>
            <p><strong>Use:</strong> Cardiogenic shock with low output</p>
            <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Tachyarrhythmias, hypotension</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--amber);">Milrinone (Primacor)</div>
          <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
            <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 0.125‚Äì0.5 Œºg/kg/min</p>
            <p><strong>MOA:</strong> PDE-3 inhibitor (inodilator)</p>
            <p><strong>Use:</strong> For HF/cardiogenic when dobutamine inadequate</p>
            <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Hypotension, arrhythmias; renal dosing</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--red);">Epinephrine</div>
          <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
            <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 0.02‚Äì0.2 Œºg/kg/min</p>
            <p><strong>MOA:</strong> Œ≤1/Œ≤2 + Œ± (dose-dependent)</p>
            <p><strong>Use:</strong> Anaphylaxis, refractory septic shock, arrest</p>
            <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Tachyarrhythmias, lactate rise</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">Phenylephrine (Neo-Synephrine)</div>
          <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
            <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 0.2‚Äì1 Œºg/kg/min</p>
            <p><strong>MOA:</strong> Pure Œ±1 vasoconstrictor</p>
            <p><strong>Use:</strong> Vasodilatory or neurogenic shock, anesthesia-induced hypotension</p>
            <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Reflex bradycardia, ischemia</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--purple);">Dopamine (Intropin)</div>
          <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
            <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 5‚Äì20 Œºg/kg/min</p>
            <p><strong>MOA:</strong> Dose-dependent (Œ≤1 then Œ±1)</p>
            <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> Replaced by norepinephrine in sepsis; avoid low-dose "renal protection"</p>
            <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Arrhythmias; "renal dose" myth</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Algorithms -->
    <div class="intro">
      <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--purple) 0%, var(--indigo) 100%);">üîÑ Algorithms (Diagnostic & Management)</div>
      <div class="alg-grid">
        <!-- A. Undifferentiated Hypotension -->
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--green);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--green);">üö® A. Undifferentiated Hypotension (Shock)</div>
          <div class="center">ABCs ‚Üí O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí monitors ‚Üí 2 large-bore IV/IO</div>
          <span class="arrow">‚Üì</span>
          <div class="center"><strong>Give balanced crystalloid bolus</strong> (500-1,000 mL)</div>
          <span class="arrow">‚Üì</span>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Warm skin + bounding pulse</strong> ‚Üí distributive
              <ul><li>Sepsis ‚Üí cultures + broad antibiotics + norepinephrine; fluids; source control</li>
              <li>Anaphylaxis ‚Üí IM/IV epinephrine + antihistamines + steroids</li></ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Cold/clammy, narrow PP</strong> ‚Üí hypovolemic/cardiogenic/obstructive
              <ul><li>Trauma/bleeding ‚Üí massive transfusion & hemorrhage control</li>
              <li>JVD, rales, S3 ‚Üí cardiogenic ‚Üí norepi ¬± dobutamine; revascularize</li>
              <li>Sudden PEA/JVD ‚Üí obstructive ‚Üí treat tamponade/PTX/PE immediately</li></ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <div style="margin-top:10px; font-weight:700; font-size:14px;">
            <strong>Targets:</strong> MAP ‚â•65, UOP ‚â•0.5 mL/kg/h, clearing lactate, improving mentation
          </div>
        </div>
        <!-- B. Septic Shock -->
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--red);">üî• B. Septic Shock‚ÄîFirst Hour</div>
          <ol style="font-size:14px;">
            <li>Draw <strong>blood cultures</strong> (don't delay therapy)</li>
            <li>Start <strong>broad-spectrum antibiotics</strong></li>
            <li><strong>30 mL/kg balanced crystalloid</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Norepinephrine if MAP <65</strong> after fluids (¬± vasopressin add-on)</li>
            <li><strong>Source control ASAP</strong>, glucose <180, monitor UOP & lactate</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
        <!-- C. Neurogenic Shock -->
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--amber);">üß† C. Neurogenic Shock</div>
          <div class="center">Fluids ‚Üí if persistent hypotension with bradycardia</div>
          <span class="arrow">‚Üì</span>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Norepinephrine or phenylephrine</strong></li>
            <li>Maintain spinal perfusion targets</li>
            <li><strong>Atropine for profound bradycardia</strong></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <!-- D. Cardiogenic Shock -->
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--blue);">üíî D. Cardiogenic Shock (AMI)</div>
          <div class="center">O‚ÇÇ, analgesia ‚Üí correct K/Mg</div>
          <span class="arrow">‚Üì</span>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Norepi for MAP</strong> ‚Üí add dobutamine for inotropy if needed</li>
            <li><strong>Early revascularization</strong> ¬± IABP if refractory</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <!-- E. Anaphylaxis -->
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--purple);">üêù E. Anaphylaxis</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Epinephrine</strong> ‚Üí antihistamines ‚Üí steroids</li>
            <li>For airway/ventilation, consider nebulized Œ≤-agonists for bronchospasm</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <!-- F. Mechanical Ventilation -->
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: #2e7d32;">
          <div class="h" style="background: #2e7d32;">ü´Å F. Mechanical Ventilation‚ÄîInitial & Adjustments</div>
          <div class="center"><strong>Initial:</strong> AC mode; RR 12‚Äì16; Vt 6‚Äì8 mL/kg (IBW); FiO‚ÇÇ 100% ‚Üí titrate ‚â§60%; PEEP 5</div>
          <span class="arrow">‚Üì</span>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li>If low PaO‚ÇÇ ‚Üí ‚ÜëFiO‚ÇÇ or ‚ÜëPEEP</li>
            <li>If high PaCO‚ÇÇ/low pH ‚Üí ‚Üëminute ventilation (‚ÜëRR or ‚ÜëVt)</li>
            <li><strong>Watch for:</strong> barotrauma, ‚Üìpreload ‚Üí hypotension, VAP</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <!-- G. ARDS -->
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--indigo);">üí® G. ARDS</div>
          <div class="center"><strong>Criteria:</strong> bilateral infiltrates + PaO‚ÇÇ/FiO‚ÇÇ < 200 + PCWP ‚â§ 18 + acute onset</div>
          <span class="arrow">‚Üì</span>
          <div class="center"><strong>Management:</strong> intubate; low Vt (6 mL/kg), adequate PEEP, FiO‚ÇÇ ‚â§60%, treat cause</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Pitfalls & Look-Alikes -->
    <div class="intro" style="border-bottom:3px solid #ecf0f1;">
      <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--red) 0%, #d32f2f 100%);">‚ö†Ô∏è Pitfalls & Look-Alikes ‚Äî NBME Trap Deck</div>
      <div class="pit-grid">
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--red);">Early Shock Recognition</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p>The first sign of hypovolemic shock is <strong>tachycardia</strong> (not hypotension). BP may be normal early.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">Warm vs Cold Shock</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p><strong>"Warm shock" = distributive</strong>; don't confuse with fever alone. The other shocks are "cold."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--teal);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--teal);">Dopamine Myth</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p>Low-dose <strong>"renal dopamine"</strong> doesn't protect kidneys‚Äîmyth. Use volume optimization instead.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--purple);">Normal Saline Trap</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p>Massive NS ‚Üí <strong>hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis</strong>; prefer LR for large-volume resuscitation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: #2e7d32;">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: #2e7d32;">Neurogenic Clue</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p><strong>Shock + bradycardia ‚Üí neurogenic</strong> until proven otherwise.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--indigo);">PEEP Effects</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p>PEEP improves oxygenation but can <strong>drop preload ‚Üí hypotension</strong>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--red);">Vent Adjustments</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p><strong>PaCO‚ÇÇ problems ‚â† oxygenation problems</strong>: adjust minute ventilation for CO‚ÇÇ; FiO‚ÇÇ/PEEP for O‚ÇÇ.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--amber);">ARDS vs CHF</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p><strong>PCWP ‚â§18</strong> with bilateral infiltrates ‚Üí ARDS, not CHF.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--magenta);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--magenta);">Sepsis Delays</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p>Don't delay <strong>antibiotics for cultures/imaging</strong> in septic shock.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">Resuscitation Fluids</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <p><strong>Dextrose-containing fluids are not for initial resuscitation.</strong></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Micro Pearls & Numbers -->
    <div class="intro">
      <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--indigo) 0%, var(--indigoDeep) 100%);">üíé Micro Pearls & Numbers Worth Memorizing</div>
      <div class="micro-grid">
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--red);">ABCs & Intubation</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">ABCs always first; <span class="highlight">GCS ‚â§ 8 ‚Üí intubate</span>.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--blue);">UOP Target</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">Urine output target: <span class="highlight">‚â•0.5 mL/kg/hr</span> (adults).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--green);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--green);">Shock Hemodynamics</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">
            <strong>Hypovolemic:</strong> PCWP ‚Üì, CO ‚Üì, SVR ‚Üë<br/>
            <strong>Cardiogenic/obstructive:</strong> PCWP ‚Üë, CO ‚Üì, SVR ‚Üë<br/>
            <strong>Neurogenic:</strong> PCWP ‚Üì, CO ‚Üì, SVR ‚Üì<br/>
            <strong>Distributive:</strong> PCWP ‚Üì/N, CO ‚Üë, SVR ‚Üì
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--purple);">Vent Starting Point</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">AC, RR 12‚Äì16, <span class="highlight">Vt 6‚Äì8 mL/kg (IBW)</span>, FiO‚ÇÇ 100% ‚Üí titrate ‚â§60%, PEEP 5.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: #5d4037;">
          <div class="h" style="background: #5d4037;">ARDS Criteria</div>
          <div style="font-size:14px;">Bilateral infiltrates, <span class="highlight">PaO‚ÇÇ/FiO‚ÇÇ < 200</span>, PCWP ‚â§ 18, acute onset, underlying cause present.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Rapid Fire Exam Tips & Vignettes -->
    <div class="intro" style="border-bottom:3px solid #ecf0f1;">
      <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #ff5722 0%, #bf360c 100%);">üöÄ Rapid Fire Exam Tips & Vignettes</div>
      <div class="rf-grid">
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--red);">1Ô∏è‚É£ Hypotension + fever + warm extremities</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Septic shock; fluids + norepinephrine + early antibiotics</li>
            <li><strong>Learning objective:</strong> Start vasopressors after initial fluids; don't delay abx</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Dopamine "boosts kidney perfusion." (It doesn't.)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--blue);">2Ô∏è‚É£ Earliest sign of hypovolemic shock</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Tachycardia is the earliest sign</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Recognize compensated shock</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Wait for hypotension</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--amber);">3Ô∏è‚É£ Spinal cord injury + hypotension + bradycardia</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Neurogenic shock</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Identify shock type by HR and skin</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Mislabel as hypovolemia because BP is low</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--purple);">4Ô∏è‚É£ Massive PE suspected with instability</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Give thrombolysis/embolectomy now; don't wait for CT</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Treat obstructive shock by removing obstruction</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> "Confirm with CTA first."</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--magenta);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--magenta);">5Ô∏è‚É£ Bilateral fluffy opacities; PaO‚ÇÇ/FiO‚ÇÇ 160; PCWP 12</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> ARDS ‚Üí low Vt 6 mL/kg + PEEP</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Differentiate ARDS vs CHF using PCWP</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Give diuretics alone</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--teal);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--teal);">6Ô∏è‚É£ Vent changes for hypercapnia</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Increase minute ventilation (‚ÜëRR or ‚ÜëVt)</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> CO‚ÇÇ is ventilation</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Raise FiO‚ÇÇ</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--blue);">7Ô∏è‚É£ Vent changes for hypoxemia</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Increase FiO‚ÇÇ or PEEP</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> O‚ÇÇ is oxygenation</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Increase RR only</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: #2e7d32;">
          <div class="h" style="background: #2e7d32;">8Ô∏è‚É£ Large-volume NS resuscitation</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Non-gap metabolic acidosis (hyperchloremic)</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Choose LR for big volumes</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> "NS is always safest."</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--indigo);">9Ô∏è‚É£ Anaphylaxis treatment order</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Epinephrine first, then H1/H2 blockers and steroids</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Treat the pathophysiology (vasodilation/bronchospasm)</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Start with antihistamines alone</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--red);">üîü IABP in cardiogenic shock</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Improves coronary perfusion and reduces afterload‚Äîbridge for refractory cardiogenic shock</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Know when to use mechanical support</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Give more fluids (worsens pulmonary edema)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--amber);">1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Ventilator weaning fails</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Due to hypophosphatemia‚Äîreplace PO‚ÇÑ</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Common reversible weaning barrier</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Increase sedation</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--purple);">1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ PCWP >18 with dyspnea and crackles</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Cardiogenic pulmonary edema, not ARDS</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Use wedge to separate CHF vs ARDS</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Intubate and call it ARDS without hemodynamics</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--blue);">1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ UOP <0.5 mL/kg/hr during resuscitation</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Give more volume unless signs of overload</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> UOP as endpoint</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Start diuretics reflexively</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--green);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--green);">1Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ PaO‚ÇÇ adequate on 100% FiO‚ÇÇ</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Titrate FiO‚ÇÇ down to ‚â§60% to avoid oxygen toxicity</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> FiO‚ÇÇ stewardship</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Keep it at 100% "just in case"</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="h" style="background: var(--red);">1Ô∏è‚É£5Ô∏è‚É£ Tension pneumothorax on vent</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Answer:</strong> Sudden hypotension & desaturation ‚Üí disconnect from vent & needle decompression</li>
            <li><strong>Objective:</strong> Recognize barotrauma complication</li>
            <li><em>Why wrong seemed right:</em> Order portable CXR first</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Final Wrap -->
    <div class="intro">
      <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--green) 0%, #388e3c 100%);">üéØ Final Wrap</div>
      <div class="tiles" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(350px, 1fr)); gap:20px;">
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--green);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--green);">üö® Shock Classification</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li>Classify shock by <strong>skin, HR, and hemodynamics</strong></li>
            <li>Fluids early, then <strong>norepinephrine for distributive</strong></li>
            <li>Treat the cause for cardio/obstructive</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--red);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--red);">üìä Hemodynamic Profiling</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li>Profile with <strong>PCWP/CI/SVR</strong> when unclear</li>
            <li><strong>PCWP ‚â§18</strong> with bilateral opacities ‚Üí ARDS</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--amber);">ü´Å Ventilator Care</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li><strong>Vt 6‚Äì8 mL/kg IBW</strong>, FiO‚ÇÇ ‚â§ 60%, PEEP for oxygenation</li>
            <li>Adjust <strong>minute ventilation for CO‚ÇÇ</strong></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
          <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">‚ö†Ô∏è Key Pitfalls to Avoid</div>
          <ul style="font-size:14px;">
            <li>Dopamine "renal dose"</li>
            <li>Excessive NS</li>
            <li>Delaying antibiotics/source control</li>
            <li>Missing neurogenic bradycardia</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p style="margin:18px 0 0 0; font-weight:700; text-align:center;">End of Chapter ‚Äì Critical Care</p>
